{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_locust_ver01/data/sn93053726/00271763165/1908050201/0026.xml":{"full_text":"WATER BURY EVENING DEMOCRAT, SATURDAY, MAY 2. 190&\nr\n(The IVpw Mayor\nBasbiI on GM.Drondhursfs Successhi PUg?\nI\nBWS 'MAN\nnmma\nCHAPTER XIV.\nTHE first committee room that\nlay to the right of HorrJgan's\noffice in the same relation to it\nas the antechamber to the left\nwas usually given over to dry offl\nclal business, and Its musty walls must\nalmost bave experienced a distinct\nshock about this time as Dallas Wain\nwright entered from the corridor be\nhind. She was accompanied by Perry\nand by Phelan, who,' passing through\nthe corridor toward the aldermanlc\nchamber, had collided with the brother\nand sister at the committee room door.\n\"Hero's a good sight for sore eyes,\n:.Miss Wninwright,\" the alderman was\nsaying with his best air. \"But is It\nfair to ask what brings such a bunch\nof sunshine into an old p'litlcal shell\nrllke this? I'd as soon think of seeing\nHorrlgan at mass as to find you .here.\"\n\"I want to attend the aldermen's\nmeeting,\" exclaimed Dallas. \"I have\na special reason. So I made Perry\nbring me. But at the door they told\nus the gallery was so crowded that w\ncouldn't\"\n\"Never you mind the gallery; miss,\"\ninterrupted Phelan. \"It isn't meant\nfor the likes of you anyway. You\nJust sit here a few minutes, an' I'll\ncatch an attendant somewhere an\"\nmake him hustle up a couple of good\nchairs for you on the main floor, where\nyou can pipe everything just like you\nwere In your own op'ra box coppln' off\na swad of high C's.\"\n\"Thank you so much, alderman,\" re\nplied Dallas. \"I hope we're not put\nting you tOitoo much trouble.\"\n\"No trouble at all. An', even if it\nwas I'd come a-runnin' to meet It. I'm\nthe original trouble eater. Besides, the\nbest In the bouse. is none too good for\nthe lady who was so int'rested in my\noutings. So long! I'll be right back.\"\n\"What a queer chap lie is!\" mused\nTerry, as Phelan hastened away on\nhis mission.. \"If I could take a six\nweeks course in slang and hot air\nfrom that man I'd be able to sew but\ntons on the whole English language.\"\n\"I don't think you need very much\ntuition,\" observed Dallas. \"But It was\nkind of Mr. Phelan to look after us. I\nlike him be\"-\n\"Because he's standing by Bennett\no plucklly In this fight?\"\n\"Mr. Bennett is nothing to me.\"\n\"Not\", asked Terry In innocent\namihse. \"Then I wasted a lot of good\ncigarette money cabling to you about\nhis campnign when you were across\nthe big woh last summer. ForNa\nman who was 'nothing' to you you\nsure took large swads of intelligent in\nterest. Look here, little girl,\" be went\noo, less flippantly, \"what's the matter?\nHas anything\"-.\n\"Nor she broke Id, with a miserable\neffort at courage. \"Nothing's the mat\nter. I'm perfectly happy. Why shouldn't\nII be? An engaged girl is always\"\n\"An engaged girl!\" he shouted in\nIgh glee. \"Von don't mean to say\nou and Alwyu\"\n\"Of course not. I am engaged to\nr. Gibbs.\"\nGood Lord!\" gasped the Ind in hon-\nt dismay. \"If that's meant for a\noke, it's the pnnkest ever! Did\"\n\"It Isn't a Joke, Terry, and it's very\nide of you to talk so. I am engaged\no Mr. Gibl. and\"-\n\"But how when did the atrocity\ncome off, and\"\n\"I became engaged to him the night\nof the administration ball. I didn't\nwant to tell you yet, because I knew\n-you don't like Dim. I'm I'm\"\n\"You're happy?\"\n\"Certainly I am!\" she retorted do\nlantiy. \"So happy that I\"-\n\"That you are having a fight to keep\nfrom crying this blessed minuter ha\nfinished. \"Say, Dallas, It breaks ma\nall up to baro you so miserable. I\nthink a whole lot of you. More'n of\nany one else bot Cynthia. And I want\nto help you out of this measly mlxup.\nWon't you?\"\n\"There la nothing any ona can do,\"\naha murmured sadly. \"I have chosen\nmy course and I\"\n\"Cheee It!\" whispered Perry in hur\nried admonition. \"Here cornea Ben\naett, and Tbelan's with him.\"\nThe young mayor came in, talking to\nthe alderman as he came.\n\"This room's disengaged,\" he was\nsaying. \"I'll write it here and give it\nto oh, I beg your pardon.\" be broke\noff. recopnlilng Dallas and Terry. \"I\ndidn't kuoW-r\nTt got two good seats for you.\"\nannounced Phelan. \"Bight where yon\ncan ae an' bear the whole shootln'\nnatch. An' I giiess before the meetin'e\nret it'a liable to get as interestln' aa\na double \"Uncle Tom\" show in a tent.\nI'll show yon the way as soon as\nyou're ready. There's no rush. Things\nain't began to sizzle on yet\"\nBennett had crossed tq where Dallas\nstood Irresolute and. under cover of\nPbelan'a talk with Perry, as Id to her.\nwith a certain unconscious stiffness:\n\"I fear I wsa too taken aback by\nfour anocaseemeot the other renins\nto remember to congratulate yoo. but\npleas hollar me when I say I wish\nyon every happiness In the new Ufa\nJog hire chosen.\"\nTbaak yon very much.\" faltered\niMllaa.\nTbera'waa aa awkward paase; Utea\naha said:\nTm casa la here to write some\nthing. Taa afraid we an detaining\nyo- To Burst be nosy with your\nCgfat antes the Boron gh bill. Too\nare quite determined to coo tiEe It ta\nthe eadT\"\nTa the Mtter eadr he answered\nmiserably. \"Even tbcntt that rod\nran bold aotiiing bat bitternea for\nT art aagaish la kla face aaorod\npaia ttfojkaa she dared cashes\neven to hereif.\n\"I am sorry,\" she said softly.\n\"It is the course I have chosen,\" he\nanswered, with a shrug, \"and If It\nleads to' eternal darkness instead of\nthe sunlight I expected I must follow\nIt none the less.\"\n\"That Is sheer obstinacy,\" she cried,\nbattling against her own heart's pas\nsionate plea. \"You have laid out a\nplan to ruin Mr. Gibbs, to deprive\nPerry and me of my own fortune,\nto enrich your\nself by selling\nBorough, stock\nshort and then\nvetoing the bill\nso that the stock\nwould collapse.\nYou have done\nall this; and yet\nyou talk of fol\nlowlng your\nabominable\ncourse to the\nend!\"\n\"Dallas,\" he\nsaid very quiet\nly, \"you don't\nunderstand, and\nKDalla$,\" he tald very you refused to\nrictlv, \"you don't me to ex\nplain, so I can\nsay no more. But one day you may\nlearn the cruel mistake you are mak\ning.\"\n\"Mistake?\"\n\"I don't mean that you are mistaken\nin choosing Gibbs Instead of me, but\nthat you are wrong In your judgment\nof what I am doing. -I hope you will\nunderstand some day. It will be too\nlate to change anything then, but at\nloast I shall be set right in your eyes.\nAnd that means more to me than you\ncan ever know.. Goodby.\"\nHe left the room abruptly, and Dal\nlas stared after blm, her brain awhlrl\nwith conflicting thoughts.\n\"There's a man In ten million, miss,\"\nvolunteered Phelan, breaking In on her\nreverie, \"an' from the looks of that\nbran' new dinky, three-k spark ou\nyour finger I guess youjre wise to the\nfact\"\n\"I am engaged to Mr. Gibbs,\" replied\nDallas coldly.\n\"What the\" gasped Phelan, check\ning himself just in time. \"I'm sure\nsorry for you, miss,\" he went ou, with\na sincerity that precluded any offense,\n\"for frleu' Gibbs la going to have\nsomething so heavy fall on his bank\nroll by the time we're through with\nthis Borough bill that he'll be able to\nuse his wad for a book mark without\ncrinklin' any of the leaves. Why,\nhe'll\"-\n\"Come, Perry,\" Interrupted Dallas.\n\"Shall we go to the meeting now?\"\nConfused, she turned to the door\nleading into Horrigan's room Instead\nof that opening on the corridor and\nfound herself face to face with her\nuncle, the boss and Gibbs.\n\"I beg your pardon,\" she began, sur\nprised. \"I didn't know\"\n\"Dallas!\" exclaimed Gibbs and Waln\nwrlgbt In the same breath. Horrlgan\nscowled at the Interruption as all three\nmen rose to their feet.\n\"What brings you to' a place like\nMs's\" asked Watnwrlgtit In displeas\nure. \"Terry and I,\" Indicating her broth\nit, who bad followed her into the\nojiu, \"are going to attend the niect\nii; of the board of aldermen.\"\nBut,\" protested her nncle disapprov\n.utfy. \"it is hardly the sort of\"-\n\"My fortune and Terry's and that of\nthe man I am to marry are all bound\nup in the Borough bill,\" she answered\nfearlessly. \"I have, a right to be pres\nent when that bill V fate is decided.\"\n\"Good nem!\" applauded Horrlgan.\n\"You're a thoroughbred. If there were\nmore women like you\"\n\"Mr. Horrigaa.\" reported Williams,\nhurrying In from an antechamber, \"the\npolice have come, and\"\n\"All right,\" answered the boas. \"Give\nthe sergeant his orders.\"\n\"I-I hardly like the responsibility,\"\nmuttered Williams, \"and\"\n\"But you'll Uke It I'm backing\nyon. fly the way, get aeata for Misa\nWalnwrtght and her brother. Get\nthem close to the anteroom door, so If\nthere's a row she can come back here.\nIf there are no vacant aeata there,\nclear a couple of people out and mate\nplace for\"\n\"But we have aeata.\" protested Dal\nlas aa Williams sned on his errand.\n\"Alderman Phelsn\n\"Alderman Fhclcn will have trouble\nfinding a aeat In this city when I'm\ndone with him,\" snarled Horrigan.\n\"Better take the aeata I offer, Misa\nWalnwrlght. They're aafcr.\"\n\"But protested Walnwrlght \"If\nthere's to be any danger ah mustn't\nbe there. I caa't tav\"\n\"I will be on hand to help her If\nthere to.\" r\"w- ---\"wl him.\n(To as Continued.)\nPerils In River lee.\nAlbany. X. V, May Z Zones of dan\neroaa pollution la tb waters of the\nHudson and Mohawk rivers from\nwhich Ice Is harvested are reported to\nexist In the vicinity of Albany. Troy.\nSchenectady and otbr places aloog\nthe npper Hudson and lower Mohawk\nvalleys In a statement msde public by\nthe state health department The\nratting of Ice from tbee Bekls should\nbe prohibited.\" says the report\nHSee Speak la Ithaca.\nlibera. X. T- May 2. Governor\nChart E. Ilnche rpnke at a monster\nmm meeting mi tb rare track gam\nbling bill, aad bin addrss was re\nceived with great entbastasn by o\nef the larva asdncea that r filled\nthe Lyfm theater. Several ha ad red J\npersona were turned away. J\nBOOSTERS ORGANIZE.\nForm National Prosperity Asso\nciation In St. Louis.\nFAITH IN FUTURE THEIR CRY.\nTo Keep Dinner Pail Full, Pay Car\nGoing, Factory Busy, Workman Em\nployed and to Maintain Present\nWages Is Object of Movement.\nSt, Louis, May 2. A business organ\nization to be known ns the National\nProsperity Association of St. Louis has\nbeen formed as the result of a confer\nence held by business men during the\nlast three dtiys, and a formal address\nwas Issued to the business interests of\nthe country. It Is proposed to extend\nthe ramifications of the association\nthroughout the country for the better\nment of all classes of business. It is\nstated that the association has for Its\nobject the encouragement of the return\nof prosperity and uplifting of business\nInterests generally,- V;\nThe officers of the association com\nprising the executive committee are:\nChairman. E. C. Simmons, formerly\npresident of the Simmons Hardware\ncompany; vice chairman, W. K. Bixby,\nformerly president of the American\nCar and Foundry company.\nPurpose of the. Association. K\nIn the formal address it is Bet forth\nthat the purpose of the National Pros\nperity Association of St. Louis is:\nTo keep the dinner pall full, to keep\nthe pay car going, to keep the factory\nbusy, to keep workmen employed and\nmaintain present wages. The address\ncontinues:\n\"The National prosperity Association\nof St. Louis has nothing to do with the\npast. It looks forward. It Is not politi\ncal. It has a platform. The two planks\nare a square deal and a square meal\nfor every man. There is nothing fun\ndamentally wrong with the business\nsituation. The financial clouds have\nrolled by. The crop prospects, that ba-'\nsis of all things for us. are exception\nally good. We believe that we can get\nback to normal conditions quickly if\nwe will. We do not see why we should\nwait for the closing months of 190S or\nfor the spring of 1909.\n\"Commercial Sun Is Shining.\"\n\"W'e have passed the low level. The\ncommercial sun Is shining. This is the\nbusiness May day. The time for this\nmovement is ripe right now. It was\nnot ripe before.\n\"The St. Louis movement may spread\nto other communities. We hope It will.\nThe prosperity we promote Is national.\nThe plans and methods of the National\nProsperity Association of St. Louis are\navailable to any business organization\nor any individual anywhere. Our as\nsociation will welcome any helpful\nsuggestion to Increase its efficiency.\nWe are confident that if the business\nmen of the United States join in the\nSt Louis movement prosperity will be\nat full tide before the end of the year\nand that 1!K)9 will be the best business\nyear our country has known.\"\nChairman Simmons said:\n\"We have formed a business organi\nsation having for its object the encour\nagement of a return of prosperity\nsooner than might otherwise occur\nwithout help. We bcliov that present\nconditions are exceedingly favorable to\nthis.\"\nWill Issue 925,000,000 Bonds.\nNew York. May 2. The Public Serv\nice Corporation of New Jersey will, ac\ncording to a report reaching Wall\nstreet, shortly Issue $25,000,000 5 per\nrent gold bonds. The proceeds will be\nused to pay for equipment, reconstruc\ntion and to take up a loan of $7,500,\n000 maturing ttent yer.\nc\nThere is only one Fels-Naptba. Be sure yon jjet the genuine.\nW h a t' s' the difference\nbetween Fels-Naptha and\nother laundry soaps?\nOther soaps work only\nwhen you do. Fels-Naptha\nsoap labors while you rest,\nbut without harm to the most\ndelicate fabric. Should be\nused in lukewarm or cold\nwater o r you will never\nknow what a wonderful\ncleanser it really is.\nThe Fels-Naptha way of\nwashing is as simple as it is\neasy. You wet the pieces to\nbe washed, rub the soap on\nwell, then roll and put to soak\nfor thirty minutes.\nDuring this half hour\nFels-Naptha loosens the dirt\nand dissolves the grease.\nSaves you all the hard-rubbing on the washboard. The dirt comes\nout by light rubbing and rinsing. No scalding nor boiling, and no\nswollen knuckles or aching back from strenuous washboard work.\nYou will know the genuine Fels-Naptha by the red and green wrapper.\nThe Labor-Saving Washboard.\nMrs. Easymark\" There was a man here a few minutes ago,\nwith a patent labor-saving washboard. I don't believe in\nthese new f angled things but he was such a nice talker, I\nlet him leave one.\"\nAndy Drudge \"Fudge! That's just like some foolish women.'\nChange one form of labor for another and call it labor-saving.\nLabor-saving washboard! Bosh! Get a bar of\nFels-Naptha soap; use it according to the easy directions on\nthe wrapper in cold or lukewarm water never hot. Then\nyou'll need no new-fangled washboard or old-fashioned wash\nboiler either. Fels-Naptha soap is the real labor-saver.\"\nFels-Naptha is wash-day fast express. Imitations the slow accommodation.\nFOR A \"MOTHERS' DAY.\"\nNew Yorkers to Honor Parents on Sun\nday, May 10.\nNew York, May 2. A new holida;\nhas come to town. Here are the fact\nabout it:\nDate Sunday, May 10.\nName Mothers' day.\nObject The honoring of the be:\nmother who ever lived your own.\nObservance-The wearing of a whiti\ncarnation.\nThe Idea originated In rhlladelphln\nwhence It spread to New York, a no\nbids fair to become as widely observ\ned as many more pretentious holidays.\nMark Twnin strongly commendeti\nthe Idea.\n\"This Is a pleasure and a duty that\nwe have long neglected.\" he said. \"Ne\nthought could be more beautiful than\nthat which, prompts every man, wo\nman and child to pay such a tribute\nto those dear ones to whom we owe so\nmuch. I do not know how many on\nniversarles of 'mothers' day' I will\nsee, but on those that I have remain\nIng I will wear a white carnation, the\nemblem of purity and mother love.\"\nSpecial Session at V.enten.'\nTreutou, N. J., May 2.joveruor\nrort nas called a special session of the\nlegislature ror Friday of next week.\nThe session Is being called for the pur\npose of confirming a number of nomi\nnations the governor has to make un\nder the laws passed by the recent leg\nislature. Among the3e are the civil\nservice commissioners, members of the\nnew state board of health, a commis\nsioner of accounts and a commissioner\nf state reports.\nAILY pASHIOM YALKS\nBY MAY MAN TON\nITH THE FASHIONABLE SATIN COAT.\nCOATS of ntio make eoa tt\nthe novel testurta of\nthe season aad this\ncostoma combines eoa of black\nwith akfrt of striped black and\nwhite Ttiltaf while the coat Is\ntrimmed with the Cfar catoa\nthe bUs sod the skirt with bands\nof tb satin, so aukiof a eompwta\ncoitom. The model is oo ol\nexcept lonat grace combined\nwith simplicity and tb coat is\neoa oi the otw oocs with the\nateavca cot in ana with tb aid\nport! one aad I wr asf ta\nnaks wfc8 it 1 cble aa tb ex\ntreme l the skirt at arrva gored\nnd snad is f ricoraas atria.\nAlmost any seasonable aniUnff\ncan fee stiUied, aad tb coat\ncan be atad to snatch tb1\nakirt if tetter 1kad. altboofh\na tin Is ttoqnatioaabir smart\nlost oow. For tb trim of\natitebed bifida or tUk braid\ncoofd b eabttitsttd for the\nstriped material, aad. If thai war\nioot, the coat would Ucom\navailable for wear any,\ntown, aa aatia coats of this sort\nwill b aMca aacd for add wrap\nthroor boat th ataaoo.\nxor to median srs wb\nrepaired, tor tke coat 4 yard of\nmaterial 21. 2 yarda or f V\nyfrde 41 locbcs wt for tb\nakh-t IV Tiros 21, 1 lard 27\nr 4'i yards 44 aaar wid af\nthrr a at e er Mti bat\naboofd tbtr b ftfor ar nap.\nV Tarda 21. r.rd 27 a,\nyards 44 Incbra wtd wi3 ba\nBdd wttb 2 yard 21 aacbra\nwtd fortbs b a a d s A\nMay Raatoa tmttara of th coat,'\nNo. 59aZ etna 34 to 42 tocW\nboat, e aft ha skat, hx Ui\nsue 22 ta 30 bear wat. was\nt au&rd to say addraaa by tb\nFashioai Drptrtmcat 4 th\nsafe receipt of tea crate tor\naca. tu m hast ed aa\nAirtMAl two ctat ataara lea\nInter porta oblcicaswa cor\nprsats deareryj\nSi